Tutorial for BilinearModels package¶

Jeffrey W. Miller

Introduction¶

Generalized bilinear models (GBMs) are a flexible extension of generalized linear models (GLMs) to include latent factors as well as row covariates, column covariates, and interactions to analyze matrix data (Choulakian, 1996; Miller and Carter, 2020).

This tutorial shows how to use the BilinearModels.jl Julia package to perform estimation and inference in negative binomial GBMs for count data. Please cite Miller and Carter (2020) if you use the BilinearModels.jl package for research leading to a publication.

In a GBM, the data matrix $Y = (Y_{i j})\in\mathbb{R}^{I\times J}$ is modeled by parametrizing the mean matrix $\mathrm{E}(Y)$ such that

$$ g(\mathrm{E}(Y)) = X A^\textrm{T} + B Z^\textrm{T} + X C Z^\textrm{T} + U D V^\textrm{T} \tag{1} $$

where $X\in\mathbb{R}^{I\times K}$ and $Z\in\mathbb{R}^{J\times L}$ are matrices of covariates and $g$ is a link function that is applied element-wise. The "bilinear" part $U D V^\textrm{T}$ is a rank $M$ matrix that captures latent effects due, for example, to unobserved covariates such as batch. The BilinearModels.jl package currently implements GBMs using a negative binomial outcome with log link, $g(\mu) = \log(\mu)$, specifically,

$$ Y_{i j} \sim \mathrm{NegBin}(\mu_{i j}, r_{i j}) $$

where $\mu_{i j} = \mathrm{E}(Y_{i j})$ is the mean and $1/r_{i j}$ is the dispersion, which we parametrize as $1/r_{i j} = \exp(s_i+t_j+\omega)$. We define $S = (s_1,\ldots,s_I)^\textrm{T}$ and $T = (t_1,\ldots,t_J)^\textrm{T}$. See Miller and Carter (2020) for details.


The package provides two main functions: fit and infer. The fit function takes $Y$, $X$, $Z$, and $M$ as inputs, and returns estimates of all the parameters ($A$, $B$, $C$, $D$, $U$, $V$, $S$, $T$, and $\omega$). The infer function takes $Y$, $X$, $Z$, and the parameter estimates as inputs, and returns approximate standard errors.

Overview of the tutorial¶

GBMs are highly versatile. Since various special cases of GBMs are useful for a range of tasks, we illustrate with a range of models from simpler to more complex.

Task / Illustration Sample covariates Feature covariates Latent factors
Simple normalization and exploratory analysis
Adjusting for sample covariates X
Adjusting for feature covariates X X
Testing for differences between groups X X
Testing for association X X X
Computing partial residuals X X X
Dimension reduction using latent factors X X X

We also precompute a few additional quantities of interest.











In [ ]:



     


I,J = size(Y)  # dimensions of data matrix

# Augment gene_info
gene_info[!,:GC] = center(gene_info[!,:pct_gc])  # centered GC content
gene_info[!,:log_length] = log.(gene_info[!,:seq_len])  # log of the sum of the exon lengths for each gene
gene_info[!,:log_mean_count] = vec(log.(mean(Y,dims=2)))  # log of each row mean of the data matrix
gene_info[!,:id] = [split(id,".")[1] for id in gene_info[!,:gene_id]]  # Ensembl gene ID without version number

# Augment sample_info
sample_info[!,:exr] = center(sample_info[!,:smexncrt])  # centered exonic rate
sample_info[!,:rin] = center(sample_info[!,:smrin])  # centered RNA integrity number (RIN)
sample_info = categorical(sample_info, ["smtsd","smcenter"]);  # convert smtsd and smcenter to categorical variables



     

















Simple normalization¶
We first illustrate performing a simple normalization.
Count data are often preprocessed using a transformation such as $\log(Y_{i j}+1)$ and standardizing the rows and columns.
Instead, a model-based approach to normalizing count matrices is to use a negative binomial outcome model with

$$ \log(\mathrm{E}(Y_{i j})) = a_{j 1} + b_{i 1} + c_{1 1}, \tag{2} $$
which is a special case of a GBM.  The residuals from this model can be used for downstream analyses or exploratory analysis such as visualization with principal components analysis (PCA).


We illustrate on the GTEx heart data.  First, define $X$, $Z$, and $M$ as follows.  With these choices, the general GBM in Equation (1) reduces to the simple normalization model in Equation (2).











In [ ]:



     


X = ones(I,1)  # feature covariate matrix is a column of ones (i.e., intercepts only)
Z = ones(J,1)  # sample covariate matrix is a column of ones (i.e., intercepts only)
M = 0;         # no latent factors



     















Then, to estimate the model parameters and compute the residuals, run:











In [ ]:



     


A,B,C,D,U,V,S,T,omega,logp = BilinearModels.fit(Y,X,Z,M);  # fit the model
Eps,Sigma_Eps = BilinearModels.residuals(Y,X,Z,A,B,C,D,U,V,S,T,omega);  # compute the residuals

Here, the GBM residuals are defined as $\varepsilon_{i j} = \log(Y_{i j} + \epsilon) - \log(\mathrm{E}(Y_{i j}))$ where $\epsilon$ is a small constant to make the logarithm finite; the package uses $\epsilon = 1/8$ as a default.
The residuals function also returns Sigma_Eps, which is the estimated standard deviation of each entry of the residual matrix Eps.  Having Sigma_Eps enables one to account for the uncertainty in Eps by weighting the residuals according to their precision.  For instance, we recommend using the scaled residuals Eps./Sigma_Eps for visualization purposes.


The scaled residuals can be visualized using PCA. In this data, there are two clear clusters of samples, corresponding to subtissue type ("Heart - Atrial Appendage" and "Heart - Left Ventricle").  Subtissue type is indicated by the smtsd variable in the sample information file for this data set.











In [ ]:



     


pcaplots((Eps./Sigma_Eps)',sample_info[!,[:smtsd]]);



     


















    
    



























For comparison, we could also run PCA on the log-transformed TPMs:











In [ ]:



     


# Compute standard normalizations for comparison
RPM, RPKM, TPM = standard_normalizations(Y, gene_info[!,:seq_len])
pcaplots(log.(TPM.+1)',sample_info[!,[:smtsd]])
title("PCA of log-transformed TPMs");



     


















    
    





























Exploring sample covariates using residuals¶
To explore relationships in the data, it is useful to color plots like this using a variety of covariates.  We illustrate coloring this plot using one more categorical covariate (smcenter = sample collection center) and two numeric covariates (exr = exonic rate, and rin = RNA integrity number).


One must be careful to avoid finding spurious relationships, so in practice we recommend splitting the data into an exploratory subset and a testing subset, when possible (e.g., see Miller and Carter, 2020).  That way, one can inspect any number of plots like this using the exploratory subset, select a model based on this exploratory phase, and then perform statistically valid hypothesis tests on the testing data.











In [ ]:



     


# Visualize association with sample covariates

Adjusting for sample covariates¶
Often, there are unwanted sources of variation that one would like to remove, such as technical biases.
In the PCA plots of the residuals for the simple normalization model in Equation (2), there is clearly some association with smcenter, exr, and rin which could be due to technical batch effects.  Since the exr and rin associations seems clearer and provide a plausible explanation for the smcenter effect, we consider adjusting for exr and rin as an example.


To add sample covariates to a GBM, we simply add columns to the $Z$ matrix.  That said, it is important to note that every additional sample covariate increases the dimension of the parameter space by $I$, since $Z\in\mathbb{R}^{J\times L}$ and $B\in\mathbb{R}^{I\times L}$. Thus, when $I$ is large and $J$ is small, one must be judicious in the choice of which sample covariates to include, since otherwise overfitting can occur.


The code below uses exr, rin, exr$^2$, rin$^2$ as sample covariates.  The @formula syntax from the GLM package provides a convenient way to specify design matrices, similar to the formulas used with lm in the R programming language. Here, the dependent variable y in the formula is just an arbitrary symbol.











In [ ]:



     


X = ones(I,1)  # feature covariate matrix
Z,Znames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + exr*exr + rin*rin), sample_info)  # sample covariate matrix
M = 0  # number of latent factors

Znames  # names of the columns of Z

Exploring feature covariates using residuals¶
Similarly, we can explore possible associations with feature covariates using the model residuals.  To illustrate this, we start again with the residuals from the simple normalization model in Equation (2).

To understand why, we color each gene using its log-transformed mean precision across samples (lmp), which makes it clear that the widely varying precision across genes is the reason for the skewness.











In [ ]:

Adjusting for feature covariates¶
In sequencing data, there are often technical biases associated with feature covariates such as GC content. Indeed, the PCA plot provides some evidence for moderate GC bias in the GTEx heart data.


To add feature covariates to a GBM, we simply add columns to the $X$ matrix. As in the case of sample covariates, one needs to be careful not to overfit.  Fortunately, though, in the case of feature covariates, overfitting is less of an issue when $I$ is large relative to $J$, because the dimension of the parameter space only increases by $J$ with each additional feature covariate.


Here, we illustrate adjusting for log_mean_count, GC, and GC$^2$.  The associations with these variables are effectively removed after adjustment.











In [ ]:



     


X,Xnames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + log_mean_count + GC*GC), gene_info)  # feature covariate matrix

Testing for differences between groups¶
In gene expression analysis, a common task is testing for differential expression between two groups of samples.  In more general terms, this consists of performing a hypothesis test for whether there is a difference between two sample conditions, with respect to each feature, adjusting for covariates and latent factors.


In a GBM, we do this by including a sample covariate that is a binary indicator of the sample condition to be tested.  If this covariate is in column $\ell$ of the $Z$ matrix, then for feature $i$, the null hypothesis of no difference is that $b_{i \ell} = 0$.  To perform a Wald test for $H_0 : b_{i \ell} = 0$ versus $H_1 : b_{i \ell} \neq 0$, the p-value can be computed as

$$ p_i = 2 \big(1 - \Phi(|\hat{b}_{i \ell} / \hat{\mathrm{se}}(b_{i \ell})|)\big) $$
where $\Phi(x)$ is the standard normal CDF,
$\hat{b}_{i \ell}$ is the estimate of $b_{i \ell}$, and 
$\hat{\mathrm{se}}(b_{i \ell})$ is an approximate standard error for this estimate.


The fit function in the BilinearModels.jl package provides a method of computing approximate standard errors for each entry of $A$, $B$, $C$, $U$, $V$, $S$, and $T$.











We illustrate by testing for differential expression between the "Heart - Left Ventricle" and "Heart - Atrial Appendage" subtissues.  To do so, we augment the sample covariate matrix to include subtissue type (smtsd).  We also keep the other sample and gene covariates, to adjust for unwanted technical effects.  For now, we use no latent factors.











In [ ]:



     


X,Xnames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + log_mean_count + GC*GC), gene_info)
Z,Znames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + exr*exr + rin*rin + smtsd), sample_info)  # add smtsd (subtissue type)
M = 0;  # number of latent factors



     















We fit the model just as before, and then we also run the infer function on the output of the fit function:











In [ ]:



     


A,B,C,D,U,V,S,T,omega,logp = BilinearModels.fit(Y,X,Z,M)  # fit the model

Testing for association, adjusting for covariates and latent factors¶
More generally, one may want to test whether the data exhibit significant associations with a particular covariate.  Differential expression is a special case in which the covariate is a binary indicator of group membership, however, the same method can be used with arbitrary discrete or continuous covariates.  Often, it is important to adjust not only for other observed covariates, but also for latent factors that may represent unobserved covariates such as batch effects.


To illustrate, we consider testing for age-associated genes in the GTEx heart data. To do this, we modify the $X$ matrix by removing smtsd and instead including age_numeric, which is the subject's age group, coded as a numerical value in {25, 35, ..., 75}.  Further, we adjust for $M = 4$ latent factors as an illustration.  In practice, the choice of $M$ and which covariates to adjust for can be made using an exploratory data set as discussed above. Testing for age-associated genes can then be done in exactly the same way as testing for group differences.











In [ ]:



     


X,Xnames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + log_mean_count + GC*GC), gene_info)
Z,Znames = design_matrix(@formula(y ~ 1 + exr*exr + rin*rin + age_numeric), sample_info)
M = 4;  # number of latent factors

Computing partial residuals¶
It is often useful to compute partial residuals in which some effects are adjusted out, but some are retained.  The residuals function enables one to retain selected effects by using the optional arguments rx, rz, and ru.


For example, when testing for age-associated genes, it is helpful to visualize the relationship between age and estimated expression.  A natural way of defining estimated expression is via the partial residual

$$ \hat{c}_{1 1} + \hat{a}_{j 1} + \hat{b}_{i 1} + (\hat{c}_{1 \ell} + \hat{b}_{i \ell}) z_{j \ell} + \varepsilon_{i j} $$
where $\ell$ is the index of the age_numeric column in $Z$, and $\varepsilon_{i j} = \log(Y_{i j} + \epsilon) - \log(\mathrm{E}(Y_{i j}))$ is the GBM residual as defined earlier.











In [ ]:



     


# (Continuing from the previous part, using the estimated parameters.)

# Compute partial residuals
rx = [1]           # retain these columns of X in residuals (do not adjust them out)
rz = [1,varindex]  # retain these columns of Z in residuals (do not adjust them out)
Eps,Sigma_Eps = BilinearModels.residuals(Y,X,Z,A,B,C,D,U,V,S,T,omega; rx=rx, rz=rz)

# Age variables for plotting
age = sample_info[!,:age_numeric]
unique_ages = sort(unique(sample_info[!,:age_numeric]))
unique_ages_names = sort(unique(sample_info[!,:age]))

# Plot estimated expression versus age for top hit, using GBM residuals
figure(); clf(); grid(true)
plot_association(age,Eps[order[1],:],unique_ages,unique_ages_names; showline=true)
title("$(gene_info[order[1],:symbol]) versus age (GBM)")
xlabel("age"); ylabel("estimated expression");



     


















    
    



























This plot shows the partial residuals for the top gene hit (EDA2R), retaining the effect of age (and the intercepts) while adjusting out all other covariates and latent factors.













Dimension reduction using latent factors¶
In addition to adjusting out unwanted sources of hidden variation, the GBM latent factors can be used to discover interesting sources of hidden variation.  Up to now in this tutorial, we have used PCA on the residuals to perform dimension reduction, however, PCA implicitly assumes the residuals are normally distributed with common variance.  While the scaled residuals are intended to make this approximation reasonable, the GBM latent factors provide a more principled, model-based approach to dimension reduction.


Computing GBM latent factors is slower than running PCA on the residuals, but it tends to yield noticably better results in our experience.  The improvement is presumably due to the fact that they are estimated using the model likelihood rather than using least squares on the residuals as in PCA.


To illustrate, we first consider the estimated parameters from the model that was used to test for age-associated genes (i.e., the current model from the preceding sections).  Since two dimensions are convenient for visualization, we illustrate by plotting the first two latent factors.  Specifically, the first and second columns of $V$ are roughly analogous to the first and second principal components scores, respectively.


More generally, the rows of $V$ provide a low-dimensional representation of the samples that can be used for visualization or downstream analyses.











In [ ]:



     


# (Continuing from the previous part, using the estimated parameters.)

figure(); clf(); grid(true)
plotgroups(V[:,1],V[:,2],sample_info[!,:smtsd]; s=20, ec="k", lw=0.25)
title("GBM latent factor representation")
xlabel("latent factor 1"); ylabel("latent factor 2"); legend();



     


















    
    



























In [ ]:



     


cor(V, sample_info[!,:smtsd] .== "Heart - Left Ventricle")

The clusters in the GBM latent factor representation are noticably tighter than when using PCA on the residuals.  Further, subtissue type is strongly associated with the first latent factor, and only weakly associated with the other latent factors. Thus, in this example, the first latent factor has a somewhat clearer biological interpretation than the first principal component.  Note that the model has not been given the subtissue type indicators in this example.
